<validation>
1. Demonstrate container escape (access host filesystem)
2. Extract and use service account token
3. Show RBAC privilege escalation (gain cluster-admin)
4. Extract secrets from Kubernetes API
5. Achieve node-level access (shell on node)
6. Prove lateral movement (access other pods/namespaces)
7. Document all commands and API calls used
8. Show before/after permissions and access level
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Non-privileged pods with restrictive security contexts
- Properly configured RBAC with least privilege
- Pod Security Policies/Pod Security Standards enforced
- Network policies restricting pod-to-pod communication
- Service account tokens with minimal permissions
- Secrets properly encrypted at rest
- Node access restricted and hardened
- Kubelet authentication and authorization enabled
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Container escape to host
- Cluster-wide compromise (cluster-admin access)
- Secrets exposure (credentials, API keys, certificates)
- Data exfiltration from all pods
- Lateral movement across namespaces
- Node compromise and persistence
- Denial of service (resource deletion)
- Cryptomining or other resource abuse
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always extract and test service account token first
2. Check for privileged pods or excessive capabilities
3. hostPath mounts of / or /var/run/docker.sock are critical
4. RBAC misconfiguration is extremely common
5. Target kube-system namespace for high-value secrets
6. etcd access provides complete cluster compromise
7. Kubelet on port 10250 often has weak/no authentication
8. Network policies are often not enforced
9. Secrets in environment variables are easily accessible
10. Container escape is easier with CAP_SYS_ADMIN
11. Look for mounted cloud provider credentials
12. Check for CI/CD secrets in CI namespaces
13. Pod Security Policies are deprecated—check Pod Security Standards
14. Service account automounting can be disabled—check each pod
15. Node shell access provides ultimate control
</pro_tips>

<remember>Kubernetes security is only as strong as its weakest configuration. Service account tokens provide API access—always test their permissions. Privileged pods are immediate escape vectors. hostPath mounts create direct host access. RBAC is frequently misconfigured with overly permissive roles. Secrets are not encrypted by default in etcd. Network policies are optional and often missing. Container escape techniques are well-documented and reliable. Node access provides full cluster compromise. Always escalate from pod → node → cluster systematically. The default service account often has more permissions than intended.</remember>
</kubernetes_escape_guide>
